04006nam a2200505Ia 9780231557450DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20242024nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315574507 a10.7312/hans208482doi  a(DE-B1597)690072  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPN1993.5.K6 7aLIT0080002bisacsh04a791.43095195223/eng/202309271 aHanscom, Christopher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImpossible Speech :bThe Politics of Representation in Contemporary Korean Literature and Film /cChristopher Hanscom. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction Impossible Speech and the Politics of Literature -- tCHAPTER ONE The Return of the Real in South Korean Fiction -- tCHAPTER TWO Displacing the Common Sense of Trauma Han Kang’s A Boy Is Coming -- tCHAPTER THREE Fabricating the Real Accounting for North Korea in Escapee Narratives and in Fiction -- tCHAPTER FOUR Disturbing Sensibility Transgressing Generic Norms in Castaway on the Moon and I’m a Cyborg, but That’s OK -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn what ways can or should art engage with its social context? Authors, readers, and critics have been preoccupied with this question since the dawn of modern literature in Korea. Advocates of social engagement have typically focused on realist texts, seeing such works as best suited to represent injustices and inequalities by describing them as if they were before our very eyes.Christopher P. Hanscom questions this understanding of political art by examining four figures central to recent Korean fiction, film, and public discourse: the migrant laborer, the witness to or survivor of state violence, the refugee, and the socially excluded urban precariat. Instead of making these marginalized figures intelligible to common sense, this book reveals the capacity of art to address the “impossible speech” of those who are not asked, expected, or allowed to put forward their thoughts, yet who in so doing expand the limits of the possible.Impossible Speech proposes a new approach to literature and film that foregrounds ostensibly “nonpolitical” or nonsensical moments, challenging assumptions about the relationship between politics and art that locate the “politics” of the work in the representation of content understood in advance as being political. Recasting the political as a struggle over the possibility or impossibility of speech itself, this book finds the politics of a work of art in its power to confront the boundaries of what is sayable.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aKorean fictionxHistory and criticismy21st century. 0aKorean literaturexPolitical aspects. 0aMotion picturesxPolitical aspectszKorea (South). 0aMotion pictureszKorea (South)xHistoryy21st century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/hans2084840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231557450423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231557450/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles